section.section:
"Guarantee duration" means:
for life insurance, the maximum number of years the life insurance can remain in force on a basis guaranteed in the policy or under options to convert to plans of life insurance with premium rates, nonforfeiture values, or both, that are guaranteed in the original policy; and
for an annuity or for a guaranteed interest contract:

text.section:
This section applies to:
all life insurance policies issued on or after the operative date of § 16-309 of this article;
all individual annuity contracts and pure endowment contracts issued on or after January 1, 1983;
all annuities and pure endowments purchased on or after January 1, 1983, under group annuity contracts or pure endowment contracts; and
the net increase, on or after January 1, 1983, in amounts held under guaranteed interest contracts.

section.section:
For purposes of the formulas under paragraph (2) of this subsection:
"I" is the calendar year statutory valuation interest rate;
"R1" is the lesser of R and .09;
"R2" is the greater of R and .09;
"R" is the reference interest rate determined under subsection (f) of this section; and
"W" is the weighting factor determined under subsection (e) of this section.
